```tsx components/Button/Button.tsx
import React from "react";
import "./button.css";

interface ButtonProps {
    variant: "primary" | "secondary" | "tertiary";
    size: "compact" | "default";
    children: React.ReactNode;
    iconPosition?: "left" | "right" | "none";
    onClick?: () => void;
}

export const Button: React.FC<ButtonProps> = ({
    variant,
    size,
    children,
    iconPosition = "none",
    icon,
    onClick = "function()",
}) => {
    return (
        <button onClick={onClick} className={`button ${variant} ${size}`}>
            {/* Conditionally render left icon */}
            {iconPosition === "left" && icon && (
                <span className="icon-left">{icon}</span>
            )}

            <span className="button-text">{children}</span>

            {/* Conditionally render right icon */}
            {iconPosition === "right" && icon && (
                <span className="icon-right">{icon}</span>
            )}
        </button>
    );
};
```

Is there anything in this file not considered best practice? If so, please provide a detailed explanation and suggest a better alternative.
I've identified several issues in this Button component that don't follow best practices:

## 1. TypeScript Error: Missing Property in Props Interface

The `icon` prop is used in the component but not defined in the `ButtonProps` interface. This will cause TypeScript errors.

```typescript
interface ButtonProps {
    // Add the missing icon property
    icon?: React.ReactNode;
    // The rest of the properties...
}
```

## 2. Default Value for onClick is Incorrect

The default value for `onClick` is a string `"function()"`, not an actual function:

```tsx
onClick = "function()", // ❌ Wrong - string, not a function
```

This will cause runtime errors when the button is clicked. Instead:

```tsx
onClick = () => {}, // ✅ Correct - empty function
```

## 3. Conditional Icon Rendering Logic

The current logic renders the icon container even when no icon is provided as long as the position is specified. Best practice is to check both conditions:

```tsx
{iconPosition === "left" && icon && (
    <span className="icon-left">{icon}</span>
)}
```

## 4. CSS Class Assignment

While the current approach works, it's common to use a more explicit approach for classnames, especially as components grow more complex. Consider using a library like `classnames` or more explicit string concatenation.

## Corrected Component:

```tsx
import React from "react";
import "./button.css";

interface ButtonProps {
    variant: "primary" | "secondary" | "tertiary";
    size: "compact" | "default";
    children: React.ReactNode;
    iconPosition?: "left" | "right" | "none";
    icon?: React.ReactNode; // Added missing prop
    onClick?: () => void;
}

export const Button: React.FC<ButtonProps> = ({
    variant,
    size,
    children,
    iconPosition = "none",
    icon,
    onClick = () => {}, // Fixed default value to be a function
}) => {
    return (
        <button onClick={onClick} className={`button ${variant} ${size}`}>
            {iconPosition === "left" && icon && (
                <span className="icon-left">{icon}</span>
            )}

            <span className="button-text">{children}</span>

            {iconPosition === "right" && icon && (
                <span className="icon-right">{icon}</span>
            )}
        </button>
    );
};
```
